<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="64" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1706,2018]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis box="[201,299,1850,1874]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Remarks</emphasis>
: The new species resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[645,796,1850,1874]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Erythria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rudobreva">
<emphasis box="[645,796,1850,1874]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">E. rudobreva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dworakowska" box="[814,1227,1850,1874]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" refString="Dworakowska, I. (1993) Some Dikraneurini (Auchenorrhyncha: Cicadellidae: Typhlocybinae) from south-east Asia. Orient Insects, 27, 151 - 173." type="journal article" year="1993">
Dworakowska 
<number box="[989,1049,1850,1874]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" value="1993.0">1993</number>
: 152, 153, 165
</bibRefCitation>
) but differs in its extension at the hind upper angle of the pygofer and long sclerotized appendage, and by the longer apical penis appendages and bigger apodeme.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1706,2018]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin words “ 
<emphasis box="[806,865,1960,1983]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">eury-</emphasis>
” and “ 
<emphasis box="[945,1048,1959,1982]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">projectus</emphasis>
”, referring to the broad end of the apical penis appendages.
</paragraph>
